[1]
Date: 18 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NY Times [edited]
http://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/18/nyregion/18POIS.html

Contaminated Food Sickened Six in Yonkers, Officials Say
-----------------------------------------------------------
YONKERS, May 17  After considering everything from cyanide poisoning to
bioterrorism, officials here say that six residents who became violently
ill Thursday night appear to have suffered from food contamination.
Two people were still listed in critical condition at St. Joseph's Medical
Center today, while three others were stable. A sixth person was treated
and released. The six went into respiratory arrest after eating dinner in a
Yonkers apartment. Others in the apartment who did not eat the meal did not
become sick, the police said.
Because an ambulance worker developed a rash after lifting one of the
victims, the police initially thought the incident could have been a far
more serious outbreak or attack. The rash is now believed to have been
either a coincidence or a result of contact with a victim's bodily fluids.
Until medical officials can pinpoint the cause of the illness, the
authorities are treating the case as a possible crime. "We are looking at
substances in the food," said the Yonkers police commissioner, Charles A.
Cola. "There are preservatives that can cause these symptoms. But at this
late date, we can say it wasn't cyanide."
The police responded to a call at 6:17 Thursday night for what appeared to
be an incident of food poisoning in a modest four-story row house, not far
from the city's downtown. But because of the severity of the symptoms and
the skin reaction of the medical technician, city officials went into full
crisis mode.
The Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Westchester County district
attorney's office and a team of hazardous materials experts were all called
in. The neighborhood surrounding the apartment building was closed off, as
was St. Joseph's emergency room. And the American Red Cross started to set
up an emergency shelter at a nearby church.
"We're dealing with so many unknowns in our society, as we're all painfully
aware of," Mayor John D. Spencer said at a news conference. "As a
government, as a city, we have to be prepared to be overly cautious when
dealing with issues such as chemicals or strange occurrences, which this
was yesterday."
The six victims  four men and two women of Egyptian heritage who range in
age from 23 to 60  apparently used some ingredients that were brought to
the United States from Egypt, Commissioner Cola said. "Right now I'm
leaning toward this being a non-crime, based on medical advice that it
could have happened naturally," he said.
There was no move to recall any particular food item because a number of
ingredients were used in the dinner. "We don't know what it is, so how do I
say, `It's the A.& P.'?" Commissioner Cola said.
Dr. Nicholas E. DeRobertis, director of emergency services at St. Joseph's
Medical Center, said the list of substances that could provoke such a
reaction was "pretty extensive," including certain antibiotics and food
preservatives. The patients suffered from a condition he called
methemoglobinemia, which changes the red blood cells so that they cannot
carry oxygen to the body's tissues.
"When that happens, people come in with severe respiratory distress, a
bluish color and altered mental state," Dr. DeRobertis said at the news
conference.
Mr. Cola said the patients were immediately given an antidote for cyanide
poisoning as a precaution.
Foods from the meal were being tested at a federal Food and Drug
Administration laboratory in Queens, said Heather McGill, a spokeswoman for
the Westchester County Health Department. It was not known when the test
results would be made available, she said.
[Byline: Lisa W. Foderaro]
