[2]
Date: Date: Fri, 17 May 2002 16:14:11 -0700
From: "Carol H. Knott" <ctn43074@centurytel.net>
Source: Newsday [edited]
http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/ny-bc-ny--mysteriousillness0517may17.story?coll=ny%2Dap%2Dregional%2Dwire

YONKERS, N.Y. -- Doctors blamed tainted food Friday for the sudden
illnesses that set off a chemical-contamination scare in downtown
Yonkers. The police commissioner said he doubted there had been any foul
play. Two of the victims remained in critical condition a day after the
outbreak of a rare blood-cell disease. Three were in stable condition and
one was released from the hospital.
"I'm leaning toward non-crime based on medical advice," said Commissioner
Charles Cola. "Nobody has told us this is something that somebody put in
the food." He added, however, that police were still treating the victims'
apartment as a crime scene and that "It would be presumptuous of me to rule
out foul play."
Mayor John Spencer said Yonkers was "back to normalcy" after spinning into
emergency mode Thursday night. The six victims had been taken to St.
Joseph's Medical Center with severe breathing problems, a bluish pallor and
an altered mental state. Some emergency workers reported picking up a rash
as they treated the patients, adding to the concern.
The hospital was closed briefly and police, firefighters,
hazardous-materials workers and even anti-terrorist agents streamed into
the area. The mayor mentioned the possibility of cyanide poisoning. A
decontamination shower was set up outside the victims' home. Air tests in
the building and at the hospital found no airborne contamination, however.
When police learned that people in the apartment who had not eaten did not
get sick, the investigation focused on the food. Cola said the victims,
who were identified only as being adults and of Egyptian heritage, were at
a dinner party featuring a dish with many ingredients, including a
processed food that they had brought in from Egypt.
"They became concerned about the taste of the food and quickly became ill,"
he said. He said the investigation was concentrating "on the apartment and
the food itself and the way it was prepared," rather than looking into
whether the victims had enemies who might have tampered with the food.
Dr. Nicholas DeRobertis, emergency director at St. Joseph's, said something
the victims ingested had changed their red blood cells into abnormal cells
that blocked the transfer of oxygen to tissue, a condition called
methemoglobinemia. It is unlike ordinary food poisoning, he said, in that
it is a respiratory rather than gastrointestinal illness. He said he had
seen it only once before, 15 or 20 years ago.
The doctor said the condition has more than 100 known causes, including
unsafe levels of nitroglycerin; the antibiotics known as sulfonamides; or
naphthalene, which is used in mothballs. It is also used in some food
preservatives, he said, but in that form would have to be ingested in "very
large quantities" to inflict the illness. He said tests that might show if
the food was tampered with could take weeks. The mayor said it was
premature to try recalls or other warnings about tainted food because
"there could be 100 different ways" that the toxin got into the food.
[By Jim Fitzgerald]
--
Carol H. Knott
<ctn43074@centurytel.net>

[The earlier reports on this event suggested cyanide poisoning and then
later botulism. The present reports state that the clinical picture was
consistent with methemoglobinemia. Cyanide poisoning can present with a
clinical picture similar to that seen with acquired methemoglobinemia. The
earlier report on possible botulism is difficult to understand other than a
clinical presentation of respiratory distress. A good review of
methemoglobinemia can be found at the Vanderbilt Medical College website:
<http://www.mc.vanderbilt.edu/peds/pidl/hemeonc/index.htm>
Methemoglobin is an abnormal hemoglobin that is not capable of carrying
oxygen or carbon dioxide. In adults and normal children the level of
methemoglobin is less than 1% of the total hemoglobin. Acquired
methemoglobinemia (presence of methemoglobin in the blood) results when the
rate of formation of methemoglobin exceeds the rate of reduction after
exposure to certain compounds. Nitrites and aniline derivatives are
substances which most frequently produce methemoglobinemia. Because of its
use as a meat preservative and its similarity in appearance to table salt,
sodium nitrite is frequently the cause of methemoglobinemia. Nitrites are
also present in many medicinal agents. Mosts reports of nitrate- induced
methemoglobinemia, however, are due to infants fed well water contaminated
with high levels of nitrates. Nitrate salts are converted by enteric
bacteria to nitrites which are then rapidly absorbed from the
gastrointestinal tract. Silver nitrate used on burns is also a common
source as bacteria infecting burns may similarly cause nitrite production.
Aniline and its derivitives are found in many household products such as
inks, shoe polishes, paints and varnishes, and in some red and orange wax
crayons. Other drugs commonly associated with methemoglobinemia include
phenacetin, sulfonamides, and pyridium. Benzocaine, a common ingredient of
topical anesthetics has also been known to cause marked cyanosis from
methemoglobinemia.
Symptoms of methemoglobinemia include headaches, fatigue, coma, and death.
Headache, fatigue, tachycardia (fast heartrate), weakness and dizziness do
not appear until levels reach 30- 40%. At 50- 60% oxygenation of tissues
becomes truly inadequate resulting in dyspnea (shortness of breath),
acidosis, arrhythmias (irregular heart rhythms), coma, and convulsions.
Death occurs with concentrations of about 70% and greater. Treatment
involves general supportive care and removal of any offending toxins. The
drug of choice for treating severe methemoglobinemia is methylene
blue. Severe cases may require exchange transfusion or the use of
ascorbic acid.
Methemoglobinemia has been associated with ingestion of food products
containing toxic levels of nitrites/nitrates or other substances. An
outbreak in India (ref.1) was associated with ingestion of rice
contaminated with metanil yellow used for coloring the rice. Other
outbreaks have been associated with the use of excessive amounts of sodium
nitrate (saltpetre) in the preparation of sausages and other meat products
(refs. 2,3).
More information on the etiology of the methemoglobinemia in this outbreak
would be appreciated.
1: Sachdeva SM, Mani KV, Adaval SK, Jalpota YP, Rasela KC, Chadha
DS. Acquired toxic methaemoglobinaemia. J Assoc Physicians India. 1992
Apr;40(4):239-40.
2: Kennedy N, Smith CP, McWhinney P. Faulty sausage production causing
methaemoglobinaemia. Arch Dis Child. 1997 Apr;76(4):367-8.
3: Bacon R. Nitrate preserved sausage meat causes an unusual food
poisoning incident. Commun Dis Rep CDR Rev. 1997 Mar 7;7(3):R45-7.
4: Chan TY. Food-borne nitrates and nitrites as a cause of
methemoglobinemia. Southeast Asian J Trop Med Public Health. 1996
Mar;27(1):189-92. - Mod.MPP]
